{"key":"processedPost-13718511","value":{"id":13718511,"first":13684454,"last":13720036,"when":1293986725,"utime":"01/02/11 06:45 PM","content":"Mycelium derives energy from the substrate and light.&nbsp; Lab people like to classify nature into neat little boxes where they're supposed to stay and play by the rules.&nbsp; However, nature rarely cooperates with us in that regard, and to this day science is constantly moving organisms from one classification to another.&nbsp; <br /><br />I strongly disagree with taking a religious stand on mushrooms being heterotrophs which can only derive energy from the substrate.&nbsp; My own experience and constant experimentation for 40 years shows otherwise.<br /><br />However, it's still just semantics.&nbsp; Mushrooms use light and nobody who has ever grown or observed them disputes that. It's not to tell them which way to grow. As for the original question in this thread, lighting should not be cut back once pinning starts.<br />RR","title":"Re: When pinning starts should lighting be cut back?","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}